## A.1 What the HBN profile actually does

The profile defines a single Helm chart `dpf-deployment` v25.10.1 that ships **everything in one bundle**:

| Component | Source | Role |
|---|---|---|
| `bfb` URL | `bf-bundle-3.2.1-34_25.11_ubuntu-24.04_64k_prod.bfb` | BFB image fetched + pushed to DPU |
| `dpuFlavors[hbn-v25.10.1]` | inline | Kernel cmdline, mlxconfig, OVS bring-up script — applied at BFB install |
| `dpuServiceConfigurations[doca-hbn]` | inline | Per-DPU values + NVUE-format FRR config rendered via Jinja2 |
| `dpuServiceTemplates[doca-hbn]` | `nvcr.io/nvidia/doca/doca_hbn:3.2.1-doca3.2.1` (chart v1.0.5) | The actual HBN container DaemonSet |
| `dpuDeployments[hbn-only]` | inline | Wraps DPUServices + service chains |
| `dpuServiceInterfaces` | inline | Defines `p0`, `p1`, `pf0hpf` ServiceInterfaces |
| `dpuServiceIPAMs` | inline | `pool1` (172.16.97.0/24 /29 per DPU) + `loopback` (11.0.0.0/24 /32 per DPU) |
| `dpuServiceChains` | inline | Wires p0/p1/pf0hpf physical → HBN container's `p0_if`/`p1_if`/`pf0hpf_if` |

**Observation worth noting**: the per-DPU IPAM preallocations in the profile match **our specific DPUs by serial number**:
```
allocations:
  dpu-node-mt2439600dak-mt2439600dak: 172.16.97.0/29   ← gpu2
  dpu-node-mt24326005fn-mt24326005fn: 172.16.97.8/29   ← gpu1
```
So either this profile was given to us pre-customized for this lab, or someone with our DPU serials wrote it. Either way, those allocations are hard-coded.

